surname (originally a nickname or an occupational name given to someone who was employed in a royal household). Its frequency among African Americans is no doubt partly attributable to the civil rights leader  Martin Luther King  (  1929–68 ). It is also used as a short form of   Kingsley ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kingsley","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, originally a local name derived from various places (in Cheshire, Hampshire, Staffordshire) named in Old English as <i>Cyningeslēah</i> ‘king's wood’."]}]},{"name":"Niall","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of disputed derivation; it may mean ‘cloud’, ‘passionate’, or perhaps ‘champion’. It was adopted by the Scandinavians in the form <i>Njal</i> and soon became very popular among them. From the Middle Ages onwards, this name was found mainly in Ireland, the Highlands of Scotland, and the English-Scottish Border region. However, it has been strongly revived among non-Gaelic speakers since the latter part of the 20th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Neal","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Neil ."]},{"name":"Neale","meanings":["Latin: Dark, swarthy; blacksmith."]},{"name":"Neil","meanings":["Anglicized form of the enduringly popular Gaelic name   Niall .  From the Middle Ages onwards, this name was found mainly in Ireland, the Highlands of Scotland, and the English-Scottish Border region. However, since the 20th century it has spread to enjoy considerable popularity in all parts of the English-speaking world, although in England it has recently been overtaken by the Gaelic form."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Tyrone","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name of a county in Northern Ireland and a city in Pennsylvania. Its use as a given name seems to be due to the influence of the two film actors (father and son) called  Tyrone Power , especially the younger one (  1913–58 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When King Niall of Tyrone was born in 1175, in Ireland, his father, King Áod of Tir-Eoghin, was 31 and his mother, Unknown ingen Matudan II of Ulster, was 46. He married Miss MacKenady. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1226, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1175–1226":"1175–1226","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1167–1226":"1167–1226","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1187–1260":"1187–1260","1205–1239":"1205–1239","–Female":"Surnud","1198–1255":"1198–1255","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1145–1177":"1145–1177","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1198":"1198","1187":"1187","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1130":"1130","1260":"1260","1170":"1170","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1226":"1226","1145":"1145","1255":"1255","1167":"1167","1177":"1177","Abt 1198":"umbes 1198","after 1198":"pärast 1198","about 1187":"umbes 1187","County Tyrone, Northern Ireland, United Kingdom":"County Tyrone, Põhja-Iirimaa, United Kingdom","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Tir Éoghain, Eire":"County Tyrone, Iirimaa","Clannaboy, Co. Antrim, Ireland":"County Antrim, Iirimaa","Tyrone,Tyrone,Ireland":"County Tyrone, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1175–1226":"1175–1226","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1167–1226":"1167–1226","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1187–1260":"1187–1260","1205–1239":"1205–1239","–Female":"Kuollut","1198–1255":"1198–1255","1198–Male":"1198–Kuollut","1145–1177":"1145–1177","1130–Female":"1130–Kuollut","1198":"1198","1187":"1187","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1130":"1130","1260":"1260","1170":"1170","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1226":"1226","1145":"1145","1255":"1255","1167":"1167","1177":"1177","Abt 1198":"noin 1198","after 1198":"1198 jälkeen","about 1187":"noin 1187","County Tyrone, Northern Ireland, U